<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="77" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d77">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 493.11/513.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Chargé <persName type="to">MacMurray</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-20">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 20, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>This Department does not appear to have authority affirmatively to
                            sanction the postponement of indemnity payments or the alteration of the
                            schedule, but if the postponement of the payment of deficiencies is
                            unavoidable, and a majority of the powers interested agree to wait until
                            the end of the war, it is extremely unlikely that any demand for
                            immediate payment would be made by this Government under present
                            circumstances, and this Government is willing to use its good offices to
                            that end with other powers if requested. The Department trusts that the
                            deficit will not be so large as to interfere with the support of the
                            Chinghua College.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>